Spark executors run inside JVMs. Executor heap is split into reserved, user, and unified memory. Unified memory is dynamically shared between execution memory (shuffles, joins, sorts) and storage memory (cache, broadcast). Execution has priority and can evict storage. Off‑heap memory and memory overhead are critical, especially for PySpark

reserved memory - 300 MB

user memory- 1 - (heap - 300 MB) * (1 - spark.memory.fraction) default 40% used for UDF, Scala / Python objects, Spark metadata, Deserialized rows
Unified Memory (Execution Memory + storage memory)
= (spark.executor.memory − 300MB) × spark.memory.fraction
(default 0.6)

execution memory
Shuffles,Joins (hash tables),Sorts,Aggregations,Window functions
Characteristics:
Borrowed first
If insufficient → spill to disk
Storage memory can be evicted to make room

Storage Memory
1.cache() / persist()
2.Broadcast variables

Characteristics:
Best‑effort
Can be evicted if execution needs memory
Controlled by spark.memory.storageFraction (default 0.5 of unified)

Why it’s called Unified memory
Execution ↔ Storage share memory dynamically from spark 1.6
This prevents wasted memory and reduces spills.
